## PART I: THE UNIQUE SOURCE MATERIAL CHALLENGE

### 1.1 No Single Founder, No Single Text, No Single Period

Hinduism presents the most complex source material challenge of any religious system. Unlike Islam (one primary text, one generation), Christianity (five primary authors, one century), Buddhism (one founder, one generation of foundational teaching), or Judaism (one covenant community with evolving textual tradition), Hinduism has:

- **No single founder.** No Muhammad, no Jesus, no Buddha, no Moses.
- **No single canonical text.** A textual tradition spanning over 3,000 years across multiple languages.
- **No single creedal statement.** No shahada, no Nicene Creed, no Four Noble Truths.
- **No single institutional authority.** No Pope, no Caliph, no Sangha council.

The foundational corpus includes:

```
TEXT                    APPROXIMATE DATE     CHARACTER
Rig Veda               ~1500-1200 BCE       Hymns to cosmic
                                             powers; ritual
                                             invocation

Upanishads             ~800-200 BCE         Philosophical
                                             dialogues;
                                             metaphysical inquiry

Bhagavad Gita          ~200 BCE-200 CE      Philosophical-
                                             devotional dialogue
                                             within epic narrative

Brahma Sutras          ~200 BCE-200 CE      Systematic
                                             philosophical
                                             aphorisms

Yoga Sutras            ~200 BCE-400 CE      Systematic
(Patanjali)                                  contemplative
                                             methodology

Major commentaries     ~700-1400 CE         Shankara (Advaita),
                                             Ramanuja
                                             (Vishishtadvaita),
                                             Madhva (Dvaita)
```

This temporal span (~1500 BCE to 1400 CE, approximately 3,000 years of textual production) is the longest of any religious tradition's foundational corpus. The diversity within the corpus is correspondingly vast.

### 1.2 Methodological Decision

Rather than attempting to profile the entire corpus (which would produce a meaninglessly averaged signature), I will profile the PHILOSOPHICAL CORE — the texts that contain the tradition's deepest structural claims and that have been recognized across the tradition as foundational:

**Primary:** The principal Upanishads (Chandogya, Brihadaranyaka, Isha, Kena, Katha, Mundaka, Mandukya, Taittiriya, Aitareya, Prasna) and the Bhagavad Gita.

**Secondary:** The Brahma Sutras and major commentarial traditions (Shankara, Ramanuja, Madhva) for understanding the internal interpretive diversity.

**Tertiary:** The Yoga Sutras of Patanjali for understanding the contemplative methodology.

This selection focuses on the texts that have the deepest structural content and the widest recognition across the tradition's internal diversity. It does not capture the full range of Hindu practice (temple worship, devotional poetry, festival traditions, domestic ritual) — but the metabolic protocol analyzes FOUNDATIONAL TEXTS, and these are the texts the tradition itself identifies as foundational.

### 1.3 The Advantage of Internal Diversity

Hinduism's internal diversity is not a methodological problem — it is a DIAGNOSTIC ADVANTAGE. The tradition contains within itself:

- Radical monism (Advaita Vedanta: only Brahman is real)
- Qualified monism (Vishishtadvaita: Brahman is real with real qualities)
- Dualism (Dvaita: God and world are permanently distinct)
- Theistic devotion (bhakti traditions)
- Non-theistic analysis (Samkhya)
- Contemplative methodology (Yoga)
- Ritualism (Mimamsa)

If all of these diverse internal positions share a common metabolic signature, that signature is the tradition's genuine structural core. If they don't share a signature, the tradition has no unified core — it's a family of traditions sharing a cultural label.

The protocol can determine which is the case.

