## PART III: METABOLIC SIGNATURE

### 3.1 The Complete Profile

```
ACQ:  15 (strongly catabolic)
     The "neti, neti" method systematically negates all
     limited descriptions of Brahman. Each positive
     characterization is acquired and then DISSOLVED.
     "Brahman is consciousness" → neti (not ONLY
     consciousness as we conceive it). "Brahman is
     being" → neti (not ONLY being as we conceive it).
     
     The acquisition mode is CATABOLISM APPLIED TO
     DESCRIPTION ITSELF. Every concept acquired is
     dissolved to point beyond concepts.
     
     BUT: the Bhakti tradition has a DIFFERENT ACQ mode —
     anabolic. The devotee ACCUMULATES experiences of
     the divine — visions, emotional encounters, devotional
     practice, temple worship. The bhakti acquisition
     is additive, accumulative, experiential-emotional.
     
     The tradition contains BOTH ACQ modes:
     - Jnana: ACQ 10 (extremely catabolic)
     - Bhakti: ACQ 70 (anabolic)
     - Karma: ACQ 45 (moderate — learning through action)
     - Raja: ACQ 20 (catabolic — dissolving mental
       modifications)
     
     THE MULTI-PATH SYSTEM MEANS THE TRADITION HAS
     MULTIPLE ACQ MODES OPERATING SIMULTANEOUSLY.
     This is unique. Every other tradition has a
     dominant ACQ mode. Hinduism has FOUR, explicitly
     designed for different metabolic profiles.

PRC:  MULTI-PATH
     Jnana path: PRC 10 (extremely catabolic —
       dissolves all appearances including the
       framework of dissolution itself)
     Bhakti path: PRC 70 (strongly anabolic —
       accumulates devotional experience, builds
       relationship with personal deity, preserves
       and elaborates the emotional texture of
       divine encounter)
     Karma path: PRC 50 (balanced — action processed
       through detachment; neither accumulating
       results nor dissolving action; the ACT is
       preserved but the ATTACHMENT is dissolved)
     Raja path: PRC 20 (catabolic — "yoga is the
       cessation of the modifications of the mind-stuff"
       [Yoga Sutras 1.2]; systematically dissolves
       mental activities to reveal pure awareness)
     
     THE TRADITION EXPLICITLY PROVIDES MULTIPLE
     PROCESSING MODES. The PRC is not a single
     value but a MENU of values — each appropriate
     for a different metabolic profile.
     
     This is the ONLY system where PRC is explicitly
     multi-valued by design rather than by historical
     accident.

RET:  S[45] E[25] N[10] I[10] M[10]
     
     S[45]: STRUCTURAL-IDENTITY. The structural
       content is about IDENTITY — the identity of
       self and absolute, the structural relationships
       between levels of reality, the precise mechanism
       of ignorance and liberation. The structure is
       not about ORDER (Islam) or PROCESS (Buddhism)
       or INVERSION (Paul) or COSMIC NARRATIVE
       (Christianity). It is about WHAT IS IDENTICAL
       TO WHAT at the deepest level.
     
     E[25]: EMOTIONAL-DEVOTIONAL. Genuinely high.
       The bhakti tradition ensures that emotional
       content is NOT compartmentalized (unlike Marx)
       and NOT subordinated to structure (unlike
       Paul, where E serves S). In Hinduism, E is a
       VALID PRIMARY PATH. Devotional love is as
       valid a route to liberation as analytical
       knowledge. The emotional substrate is HONORED,
       not merely tolerated.
       
       The great bhakti poets (Mirabai, Kabir, Tulsidas,
       the Alvars, Andal) produced response objects of
       extraordinary emotional depth and devotional
       intensity. These are not secondary to the
       philosophical tradition — they are PARALLEL,
       accessing the same structural depth through a
       different channel.
     
     N[10]: NARRATIVE-EPIC. The epic tradition
       (Mahabharata, Ramayana) provides a narrative
       substrate, but narrative is not the PRIMARY
       retention mode. The narratives serve as
       CONTEXTS for philosophical teaching (the Gita
       within the Mahabharata) rather than as primary
       content carriers.
     
     I[10]: IMAGISTIC-SYMBOLIC. Rich visual symbolism —
       deity forms (murti), mandalas, yantras,
       iconographic traditions. The visual channel
       is a genuine information carrier — the
       multi-armed Shiva Nataraja encodes the entire
       cyclical cosmology in a single visual form.
       But imagistic retention is a CHANNEL, not the
       dominant substrate.
     
     M[10]: MYSTICAL-UNITIVE. Direct experience of
       identity with Brahman. Samadhi (absorption)
       states. Turiya (the fourth state of
       consciousness, beyond waking, dreaming, and
       deep sleep). The mystical substrate is not
       an add-on but a CORE FEATURE — the tradition
       recognizes direct unitive experience as the
       highest form of knowledge.

PS:   80 (very high)
     Total life engagement across all four paths.
     The monastic traditions (sannyasa) require
     complete renunciation. The householder traditions
     (grihasta) integrate spiritual practice into
     family and social life. The passion is for
     LIBERATION (moksha) — pursued through whichever
     path suits the practitioner's metabolic profile.

MCL:  85 (very high)
     The structural connections, particularly in
     Advaita Vedanta, are extraordinarily precise.
     Shankara's arguments are among the most rigorous
     philosophical arguments in ANY tradition — Eastern
     or Western. The precision of the level-differentiation
     system, the adhikara framework, and the systematic
     negation method all demonstrate very high metabolic
     clarity.
     
     The MCL is slightly lower than Buddhism's 90
     because the MULTI-PATH structure means different
     paths have different clarity standards — the
     bhakti path values emotional intensity over
     analytical precision, which is appropriate to
     its channel but lowers the AVERAGE MCL across
     the system.

MD:   95+ (Level 5-6)
     The deepest sustained structural depth in any
     system analyzed. The recursive self-dissolution
     at Level 6 exceeds all other traditions.
     
     Level 5: Thou art That. Self IS absolute.
     Level 6: Even "Thou art That" dissolves. Neti,
       neti. The framework dissolves. Silence.

MC:   85 (very high)
     Sustained across lifetime through multiple
     practice traditions:
     - Daily puja (worship)
     - Meditation (dhyana)
     - Scriptural study (svadhyaya)
     - Festival cycle (maintaining temporal engagement)
     - Life-stage system (ashrama dharma — student,
       householder, forest-dweller, renunciant)
     
     The life-stage system is metabolically significant:
     it provides a TEMPORAL ARCHITECTURE for deepening
     engagement across a lifetime. Analytical depth
     expected to increase with age and life-stage.

SML:  VARIABLE BY PATH
     Jnana: SML 70 (high — solitary intellectual inquiry;
       the forest-dwelling and renunciant stages are
       specifically designed for withdrawal from social
       engagement)
     Bhakti: SML -30 (inverted — communal worship,
       kirtan/chanting, temple gathering, festival
       participation; the community ENERGIZES the
       devotional practice)
     Karma: SML 30 (moderate — engaged in the world
       but with internal detachment)
     Raja: SML 80 (very high — deep solitary meditation;
       the yoga tradition's highest practices are
       intensely solitary)
     
     The tradition accommodates EVERY SML profile.
     Introverts are served by jnana and raja.
     Extroverts are served by bhakti and karma.
     This is the metabolic literacy applied to
     social-metabolic load.

DS:   30 (low)
     The framework applies across all domains — ethics,
     cosmology, psychology, social structure, ritual
     practice, philosophical inquiry. But the MULTI-PATH
     structure provides internal flexibility that pure
     DS 20 (Islam) doesn't have. Different domains can
     be engaged through different paths. This makes the
     comprehensive coverage FLEXIBLE rather than rigid.
     
     Compare:
     - Islam DS 20: comprehensive and UNIFORM across
       all domains (one divine order for everything)
     - Hinduism DS 30: comprehensive but DIFFERENTIATED
       across domains (different paths for different
       domains and different practitioners)
     - Judaism DS 25: comprehensive but ARGUMENTATIVE
       across domains (the same interpretive method
       applied with internal diversity)
```

