## PART V: STRUCTURAL COMPARISONS

### 5.1 Hinduism vs. Buddhism: The Sibling Contrast

```
                    HINDUISM            BUDDHISM
Emergence:          Original context     Emerged from Hindu
                                         context as reform

Self:               Permanent Atman      Not-self (anatta)
                    (Self) identical     No permanent entity
                    to Brahman

Absolute:           Brahman — positive   No positive absolute
                    (being,              declared; emptiness
                    consciousness,       (sunyata) as
                    bliss)               structural feature

Depth mechanism:    Recognition of       Dissolution of the
                    pre-existing         illusion of self
                    identity             through analytical
                                         observation

Meta-cognition:     Level-               Two truths +
                    differentiation      symmetric self-
                    (3 levels) +         applied
                    adhikara             epistemological
                                         criteria (Kalama
                                         Sutta)

Authority:          Vedas as shruti      Authority explicitly
                    (divinely heard) —   undermined as
                    foundational         epistemological
                    authority            ground

Caste:              Structurally         Explicitly rejected
                    embedded             (one of Buddhism's
                                         foundational moves)

Maximum depth:      Level 6              Level 5
                    (recursive self-     (analyzer dissolves
                    dissolution of       into analysis)
                    the framework)

Level 5 move:       Thou art That →      The self observing
                    then neti neti       not-self is itself
                    dissolves the        not-self
                    framework

MCL:                85                   90

KEY DIFFERENCE:
  Hinduism: There IS something (Brahman/Atman) — and then
    even that characterization dissolves at Level 6
  Buddhism: There is NO permanent something — and this
    recognition IS the liberation at Level 5

  Hinduism posits identity, then dissolves it.
  Buddhism posits non-self without the prior identity claim.
  The endpoints are remarkably similar (dissolution of
  all fixed claims about ultimate reality) but the PATHS
  are structurally inverse:
  - Hinduism: identity → dissolution of identity-framework
  - Buddhism: non-identity → dissolution of the identifier
```

The sibling relationship is metabolically precise: Buddhism is Hinduism's CATABOLISM APPLIED TO HINDUISM'S OWN POSITIVE CLAIMS. Buddhism took Hinduism's analytical method (neti neti) and applied it more radically — dissolving not only the limited descriptions but the POSITIVE ABSOLUTE (Brahman/Atman) that Hinduism preserved.

Hinduism's response was absorptive — it incorporated the Buddhist critique into its level-differentiation system (the Buddhist perspective is valid at a certain level). Buddhism's response was to maintain its distinctness by explicitly rejecting the level-differentiation framework that would absorb it.

The metabolic analysis explains both the sibling similarity and the persistent difference with structural precision.

