                                         internal conflict
```

The critical insight: Christianity and Hinduism both have wide internal metabolic diversity. Christianity's is ACCIDENTAL (multi-author canon) and UNMANAGED (no level-differentiation system). Hinduism's is DESIGNED (four yogas) and MANAGED (level-differentiation, adhikara).

Christianity would benefit from a Hindu-type level-differentiation system — it would explain why different readings of the same text produce different theologies without requiring any reading to be declared wrong. But Christianity's foundational texts don't contain such a system, and importing one would be structurally foreign.

Hinduism's managed diversity explains why it has fewer violent schisms than Christianity despite comparable (or greater) internal theological diversity. The management framework prevents diversity from becoming division.

